The complaint rate in consumer products is a measure of how many units fail to meet customer expectations or requirements after purchase. According to the provided background knowledge, "Quality" is defined by the "defective rate at a point in time" and "manufacturing errors." While customer satisfaction (a) is related, it is a broader psychological state influenced by many factors beyond just the product's performance. Market value (c) is an economic measure. Rejection rate and specification conformance (b) are internal manufacturing metrics. In the context of reliability and quality engineering (ASQ CRE), the complaint rate is the external manifestation of the defective rate, making it the most direct measure of product quality (d) as perceived by the end-user.

