The definition of reliability includes performance under "stated conditions" for a "stated period of time." While in-house tests (a), independent lab results (c), and quality control data (d) provide controlled environments and verification of manufacturing quality, they often fail to capture the actual stresses, environmental variations, and diverse usage patterns encountered by the end-user.

Field support data (b) provides direct information on how the product is used in the real world (usage measure) and how it performs under actual operating conditions. This data is essential for identifying unforeseen failure modes, verifying design assumptions, and understanding the true reliability of the product in the hands of the customer.

